Guideline updates out of ESC encourage both earlier TAVR intervention (incl. Asymptomatic) and easier referral flow. Helpful for all main players. Tricuspid and Mitral guidelines also strengthened (+ve EW and ABT). New TRISCEND II data at 18 months showing significant reduction in heart failure hospitalizations. ABT's Navitor gets CE market for all risk profiles - very helpful and potentially adding \(>50\%\) to patient pool.

Guideline updates +ve for TAVR [+ve EW, MDT, ABT]: today the ESC/EACTS updated its guidelines for valvular heart disease, with some genuinely very helpful changes. TAVR is now to be considered for asymptomatic patients (vs. watchful waiting prior), while the age threshold was reduced to 70, which is material given the average TAVR age in Europe is around 81- 82 (prior guide was for 75 and older). Note that today in Europe, EW is the only player with asymptomatic approval. Other valves got a boost too, with Mitral valve TEER upgraded to Class Ia (recommended) for sever function (or secondary) MR, while Tricuspid TEER was upgraded to Class IIb (should be considered) for those with severe TR. Overall the guideline changes are a solid positive for all three players, shifting intervention earlier and streamlining the care pathway overall, as well as potentially accelerating referrals to Heart Teams.

EW new TRISCEND II data encouraging: Edwards also presented new data from TRISCEND II at the conference that showed at 18 months EVOQUE significantly reduced the hard endpoint- of heart failure hospitalizations with the most severe TR patients. These data also confirm that at 1- year EVOQUE delivers superior outcomes to medical therapy alone. We continue to like the EVOQUE platform, noting that while procedural mortality rates are comparatively high, it's not surprising given how sick these patients are, and ultimately mortality rates in high TR patients who don't have an intervention are often in the \(30\%\) 1- year range anyway.

ABT clinical updates helpful: at the conference ABT announced it had received CE market for an expanded indication for Navitor into low / intermediate risk patients (was previously limited to high risk). This is particularly helpful as it takes the patient risk selection question out of the equation for ABT and levels the playing field somewhat, particularly key because we estimate c. \(50\%\) of patients are actually low/intermediate surgical risk within the \(>70\) guideline age pool. The label expansion was driven by the VANTAGE trial, while had a decent safety profile (2.3% all cause mortality in 12 month follow- up of 262 patients) and no moderate or greater PVL (paravalvular lead leak) in 30 days (13.6% mild PVL). Our Base Case methodology is based on a \(\sim 19x\) 2026e EV/EBITDA multiple, reflecting a premium to the Large Cap peer set driven by stronger organic growth.
Core devices grow faster than anticipated.  Libre, Mitra/TriClip, AVEIR, and CardioMEMS expand markets and take share.  Strategically appropriate and appealing balance sheet utilization.

Dx headwinds in China prove less transitory than expected.  Core Devices slows on macro challenges and Libre penetration slows down.  Emerging markets macro slowdown / FX headwinds from a strengthening US dollar.

Our Price Target methodology is based on a \(\sim 23.5x\) EV/26e EBITDA multiple, reflecting a similar growth adjusted valuation relative to large cap peers given the more normalized outlook for TAVR growth shorter term.

TAVR re- acceleration on cath lab capacity increases. Less competition than expected from BSX  TMT growth meaningfully outpaces expectation  Company reaches clinical milestones faster than expectations
Commercial traction from Medtronic and Abbott over the long term  Potential pipeline development failures in the mitral / tricuspid  US and European reimbursement pressure on pricing over time

Our price target reflects \(\sim 14.5x\) our Base Case FY27e EBITDA discounted back to align with CY peers. We assume MDT can trade at a slight premium to comps on more sustained operational execution and in- line MSD organic growth.
Aurora EV- ICD, leadless pacing, and RDN exceed expectations.  Faster than expected share gains in cardiac ablation.  Successful placements of Hugo in robotics ahead of expectations.
Material competitive landscape headwinds (SCS, CRM, DBS, TAVR, Spine).  Unexpected operational issues on supply chain management / tariffs.
■ Slowdown in Emerging Markets (esp. China).
